<h2>Chapter 1: Description of Data</h2>

<h3>Introduction</h3>
<p>Data refers to collected facts and observations. It can be analyzed using statistical methods to make decisions.</p>

<h3>Types of Variables</h3>
<ul>
<li>Qualitative (categorical): e.g., gender, color</li>
<li>Quantitative: Numerical (Discrete & Continuous)</li>
</ul>

<h3>Mean & Weighted Mean</h3>
<p>Mean is the average; Weighted Mean assigns weights to values.</p>

<h3>Median & Mode</h3>
<p>Median is the middle value; Mode is the most frequent.</p>

<h3>Quartiles</h3>
<p>Divides data into four equal parts: Q1, Q2, Q3.</p>

<h3>Variance</h3>
<p>Measures spread of data from the mean.</p>

<h3>Coefficient of Variation</h3>
<p>Relative measure of dispersion: CV = (SD / Mean) × 100</p>

<h3>Skewness</h3>
<p>Indicates asymmetry of data: positive, negative, or symmetric.</p>

<h3>Histogram</h3>
<p>Graphical frequency distribution.</p>

<h3>Box Plot</h3>
<p>Shows min, Q1, median, Q3, max; identifies outliers.</p>

